When Enough is Not Enough
Last Monday, the faculty took an important first step toward termination the
presence of the military on campus by passing a resolution to discredit ROTC,
starting in September, 1970. The resolution passed, but we must stress the fact that
the issue was not resolved.
The faculty in direct declared ROTC incompatible with Grinnell College only for
reasons or educational philosophy, while the moral question implied in the resolution was disappointingly started. This is not. only a passive handling around while the
city burns, it is also, by virtue ot the fact that Grinnell’s military advantage still
provides the world with potential courses and/or sellers, an active feeling at those
fires. i-low partially insuiiicient it will be to say when our boys have killed and
died, "Ah yes, but Grinnell gave them no credit for their training.”
The second resolution, which provided for 3 committee to re-examine the entire
relationship at ROTC to the college, seems a result of the intellectual‘s liability to
take direct action, The power and goals oi that committee are also discussing: They
could recommend to reverse the action that has already been taken, or recommend
to completely remove ROTC from the campus. But the necessary evaluation
of ROTC should already have been completed. Action is necessary. Procrastination
in the form at this committee is an opportunity statement oi Grinnell's lack of what,
in less corporate circles than our own, might be called “gets."
Both situations make it initiative that students and concerned human beings
maintain an active interest in the matter,
Let’s not be satinﬁed with haltrmeasures that are so Weak they could be
reserved in a months time. Let's not let this week's faculty action message our
conferences, We must not let It be said that in The Time Of The homes, Grinneil
College calmly elected a few defensive parasols daily generated with colors of intellectual sell-satisfaction. The issue has not been resolved. We hope that no one on
this campus Will be content until it. is resolved, and Grinnell's complexity Wlth the
military comes to an end.
Sorry . . . But, Why Hide?
Last Friday’s faculty meeting was surreptitiously attended by a noniaculty,
outside investigator, Tlle 5&8 would like to normally apologize to Mr. Wall and
the faculty for this less than straight-forward action. We realize it was contrary
to the principles ot tree communication and understanding, the goals oi the news
paper, and studentriaculty relations. We hope this action will not lesson any trust
or desire to communicate that may exist between students and faculty,
There is no certification for a lack oi communication between elements on our
small campus. For that reason, although our unlimited attendance was wrong, the
closed nature of faculty meetings which investigated this action is also wrong.
Complete understanding cannon be gained when the important debate that the
faculty does occasionally engage in cannon be heard by interested students.
The faculty certainly should not have anything to hide train students nor should
it be made so uncomfortable by the presence oi students that it is unable to express
its opinions freely. it this is the case, then perhaps the presence oi students would
be a good teaching device to assist faculty in developing noise in public speaking
and /or honest expression.
The faculty cannon expect to remain on their pedagogical personals when dealing
with student titans by closing the door on students seeking reasonable understanding. A step toward improved student-faculty communication, consisting oi
one opening oi faculty meetings, would be a step toward a more balanced relation—
ship between student and faculty. The parental is not an effective position from
which to either teach or be taught. s. K.
