rights equality
At its April 8th meeting. the
Student Affairs Committee approved the distribution of B re.
video statement on student use
of drugs. The statement will
be given to all students early
next week. As described in its
opening paragraph, the statement “is an attempt to set
forth some basic facts and our‘
rent concerns, describe some
of the drugs used and caused
by college students, express
the formal attitude of the COL
legs toward the problem. and
set forth a policy dealing with
it."
On the subject of existing
drug laws, the policy statement
says that ”while the existing
laws may be inadequate and
are often decided as unrealistic and the product of society's
unnatural fears, these laws
must nevertheless be acknowledged in any institution's platform for dealing with situations
that arise. expenses detected
among individuals on college
computer are not always legally reasonable, but users sometimes become linked with
sources of supply that are
criminal sources. . . . Federal
law providing sale of amphetamines and barbituratw without
a doctor's prescription, or resulting of a prescription without
consent of the doctor. illegal
possession is not an offense
under federal law, but is an offense under state and local
laws, including Iowa's."
“With certain knowledge of
the presence of or use of drugs,
law enforcement officers, with
a warrant, may enter and
search student rooms, sense
drugs, and make artists, with
no obligation to notify college
officials except whatever is felt
necessary by way of courtesy
(younger and other common-use
areas may be entered without
a warrant). When such action
takes place, college officials
may be faced with a difficult
conflict of responsibilities, but
are powerless to interface, and
police have generally been proceeding without taking college
officials or anyone old into
contamination Spot
